      "id": "diagnostic",
      "type": "diagnostic",
      "uiTag": "Misconception check",
      "uiColor": "red",
      "title": "Quick question first…",
      "question": "A student carries a heavy box horizontally across a room at constant height. How much work is done against gravity?",
      "options": [
        "A lot, the box is heavy",
        "Some, they used energy",
        "Zero - the force and movement are at right angles",
        "It depends on speed"
      ],
      "correctIndex": 2,
      "misconceptionFeedback": "⚠️ Common misconception! Work is only done when force and distance are in the SAME direction. Carrying horizontally means the displacement is horizontal but gravity acts vertically - so work done against gravity is zero.",
      "correctFeedback": "✓ Exactly. Work done = force × distance IN THE DIRECTION of the force. Since gravity is vertical and movement is horizontal, work against gravity = 0."
    },
    {
      "id": "concept",
      "type": "concept",
      "uiTag": "Concept",
      "uiColor": "blue",
      "title": "Work Done and Energy Transfer",
      "bodyHTML": "When a <strong>force</strong> moves an object through a <strong>distance</strong>, <strong>work is done</strong>. Work done equals force multiplied by distance moved in the direction of the force. The unit of work is the <strong>joule (J)</strong>: 1 J = 1 N × 1 m. Work done equals <strong>energy transferred</strong> - so doing 500 J of work transfers 500 J of energy. The force must act <em>in the direction of movement</em> for work to be done.",
      "keyEquation": "W = F × d",
      "diagram": {
